# =============================================================================
#  Drain Man Inc — Environment Variables (template)
# =============================================================================
#
#  WHAT THIS FILE IS
#    A committed, secret-free template listing every environment variable this
#    project understands. Copy it to .env.local and fill in real values there.
#    .env.local is gitignored — NEVER commit real values.
#
#  LOCAL SETUP
#    1.  cp .env.example .env.local
#    2.  Edit .env.local and set the value(s) below.
#    3.  Restart the dev server:  npm run dev   (Next.js only reads env at boot)
#
#  PRODUCTION (Vercel)
#    Set the same variable(s) in:
#      Project → Settings → Environment Variables
#    then redeploy (env changes only take effect on a new deployment).
#
# =============================================================================


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#  MAILJET — booking-form email delivery                    [ server-only ]
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#  These are the environment variables the running app actually reads.
#
#  The contact / booking form (components/booking/BookingForm.tsx) POSTs to
#  app/api/contact/route.ts, which validates the submission and then sends it as
#  a transactional email via the Mailjet Send API (v3.1) directly — no Zapier /
#  Make / Formspree / webhook in between. The email goes to the company
#  (admin@drainmaninc.com by default), with Reply-To set to the customer when
#  they leave an email. This is email delivery — NOT a live calendar.
#
#  SCOPE: every var below is server-only. Do NOT add a NEXT_PUBLIC_ prefix to any
#  of them — that would ship your Mailjet secret to every visitor's browser.
#  Never commit real values; .env.local is gitignored.
#
#  ── REQUIRED ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
#  MAILJET_API_KEY     Mailjet API key — the "public"/username half of the
#                      Basic-auth pair. Mailjet → Account Settings → REST API →
#                      API Key Management.
#  MAILJET_SECRET_KEY  Mailjet secret key — the "private"/password half. MORE
#                      SENSITIVE than the old webhook url: anyone with it can send
#                      mail as you. Never log it; rotate immediately if it leaks.
#  MAILJET_FROM_EMAIL  The "From" address the email is sent AS. MUST be a Mailjet-
#                      VERIFIED sender on a domain you control (e.g.
#                      no-reply@drainmaninc.com) with SPF + DKIM set up. Do NOT use
#                      a free webmail address (gmail.com / outlook.com / …): it
#                      fails SPF/DKIM alignment and will bounce or land in spam.
#
MAILJET_API_KEY=placeholder
MAILJET_SECRET_KEY=placeholder
MAILJET_FROM_EMAIL=placeholder

#  ── OPTIONAL ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
#  MAILJET_FROM_NAME   Friendly sender name shown in the inbox. Defaults to
#                      "The Drain Man Inc" when unset.
#  CONTACT_TO_EMAIL    Where leads are delivered. Defaults to admin@drainmaninc.com
#                      when unset — only set this to route leads elsewhere.
#
# MAILJET_FROM_NAME=The Drain Man Inc
# CONTACT_TO_EMAIL=admin@drainmaninc.com

#  ── UNTIL IT'S CONFIGURED ────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#  The three REQUIRED vars above must hold REAL Mailjet values for the form to
#  send — the "placeholder" values are there only so you can see what's required.
#  Until they're real, a submission is logged to the server console (so it's
#  recoverable) and the form shows a "please call us" error — it does NOT silently
#  accept leads. Set the vars in .env.local locally and in your host's env in
#  production, then restart / redeploy (env is only read at boot).


# =============================================================================
#  The entries below are NOT read by the app today. They are listed for
#  awareness only and are intentionally left commented out. Setting them has
#  NO effect unless you ALSO make the code change noted for each.
# =============================================================================

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#  NEXT_PUBLIC_SITE_URL                             [ public · NOT WIRED YET ]
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#  The site's canonical production origin, used for SEO metadataBase, the
#  OpenGraph url, sitemap.xml entries, and robots.txt. Today this value is
#  HARDCODED as "https://drainmaninc.com" in three files that are kept in sync
#  by hand:
#      app/layout.tsx   (metadataBase + OpenGraph url)
#      app/sitemap.ts
#      app/robots.ts
#  To drive it from this variable instead, those three files must be refactored
#  to read process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_SITE_URL (defaulting to the current value).
#  Until that refactor exists, uncommenting this does nothing.
#
# NEXT_PUBLIC_SITE_URL=https://drainmaninc.com

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#  PEXELS_KEY                              [ build-time tooling · NOT RUNTIME ]
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#  Used ONLY by the optional stock-photo fetch recipe documented in
#  BUILD_CONTRACT.md. The shipped site uses local images in public/images/ and
#  never reads this at runtime. You only need it if you re-fetch new stock
#  photos via that script. Get a free key at https://www.pexels.com/api/.
#
# PEXELS_KEY=your-free-pexels-api-key
